org.jtrim.collections

Class RefLinkedList<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractList<E>
        • java.util.AbstractSequentialList<E>
          • org.jtrim.collections.RefLinkedList<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of the elements in this list
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Iterable<E>, java.util.Collection<E>, java.util.Deque<E>, java.util.List<E>, java.util.Queue<E>, RefCollection<E>, RefList<E>

    public final class RefLinkedList<E>
extends java.util.AbstractSequentialList<E>
implements RefList<E>, java.util.Deque<E>, java.io.Serializable
    A doubly-linked list implementation of the RefList interface. This implementation is very similar to LinkedList but implements the more powerful RefList interface which allows users to take full advantage of the linked list. The performance is roughly the same as the the performance of java.util.LinkedList.

    This implementation allows null elements to be stored and implements all optional operations.

    Thread safety

    Instances of this class are not safe to share across multiple concurrent threads if at least one of those threads modify the list. To modify this class concurrently, access to instances must be synchronized.

    Synchronization transparency

    Methods of this class are synchronization transparent, so they can be called in any context (e.g.: while holding a lock).

    Implementation notes

    This class does not implement fail-fast behaviour like most collection implementation. This will be fixed in the future.

      • addFirstGetReference

        public RefList.ElementRef<E> addFirstGetReference(E element)
        Adds a new element as the first (with zero index) element of this list and returns a reference to it. A subsequent call to getFirstReference() will return the same reference. The newly added element can later be replaced or removed by the returned reference even if this collection was modified since then.

        This method is effectively equivalent to calling: addGetReference(0, element).

        Implementation note: This is constant time operation.

        Specified by:
        addFirstGetReference in interface RefList<E>
        Parameters:
        element - the new element to be added to this list as the first element. This argument can be null only if this collection supports null elements.
        Returns:
        the reference which can be used to replace or remove the newly added element. This method never returns null.

The newly added element can later be replaced or removed by the returned reference even if this collection was modified since then.

        This method is effectively equivalent to calling: addGetReference(0, size()).

      • addGetReference

        public RefList.ElementRef<E> addGetReference(int index,
                                    E element)
        Adds a new element to this list with the given index and returns a reference to it. A subsequent call to getReference(index) will return the same reference. The newly added element can later be replaced or removed by the returned reference even if this collection was modified since then. To append the element to the end of this list specify the size of this list as the index.

        Implementation note: This operation requires linear time in index or size() - index whichever is lower.

        Specified by:
        addGetReference in interface RefList<E>
        Parameters:
        index - the index to which the new element is to be inserted. This argument must be greater than or equal to zero and lesser than or equal to zero.
        element - the new element to be added to this list at the given index. This argument can be null only if this collection supports null elements.
        Returns:
        the reference which can be used to replace or remove the newly added element. This method never returns null.
